The Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) estimates that 400,000 could be eligible for Carer’s Allowance but don’t claim. Carer’s Allowance is a social security benefit given to people who care for someone for at least 35 hours per week.. The person they’re caring for will also need to be receiving certain benefits. The person they care for must already be receiving one of the following: Care includes tasks such as help with washing and cooking, taking them to doctors appointments and help with households tasks e.g. managing bills and shopping. Britons must be 16 and over, living in England, Scotland or Wales for at least two of the last three years. READ MORE: Over 60s could miss out on free bus pass due to state pension age changes People can’t be paid extra if they care for more than one person. If someone else also cares for the same person as they do, only one of them can claim Carer’s Allowance. For each week someone get Carer’s Allowance they’ll automatically get National Insurance credits. How to applyBritons can apply online, send an application through the post. The application form can be found on the Government website. When applying, people need to have their: People also need details of the person they care for. They need their: Claims can be backdated by up to three months. Carer’s Allowance can affect the other benefits that both the person and the person you care for get. When claiming Carer’s Allowance, the person they care for will usually stop getting: Britons can use the benefits calculator on the Government website to work out how their other benefits will be affected. People living in Scotland and get Carer’s Allowance, may also get Carer’s Allowance Supplement.